FAO suggest, that 1/3 of food produced for human consumption is lost or waste globally, which amounts in 1.3 billion tons per year (FAO, 2011, Global food losses and food waste).

The food losses vary heavily depending on the type of food and geographic location. The food losses/waste occurs in five basic stages of the lifecycle of the product;

1) Agricultural production
2) Post-harvest handling and storage
3) Processing
4) Distribution
5) Consumption

The losses during the forth stage - the distribution - are recorded in the market.

Literature suggest (FAO, 2011, Global food losses and food waste), that the losses of fruits and vegetable distribution are approximately 12%. The losses during the forth stage - the distribution - are recorded in the market.

The food losses vary heavily depending on the type of food and geographic location. The food losses/waste occurs in five basic stages of the lifecycle of the product;

1) Agricultural production
2) Post-harvest handling and storage
3) Processing
4) Distribution
5) Consumption

The losses during the forth stage - the distribution - are recorded in the market.

Literature suggest (FAO, 2011, Global food losses and food waste), that the losses of fruits and vegetable distribution are approximately 12%.
